ALAN SEALES: Keep it going.

00:15:52.590 --> 00:15:53.850
[APPLAUSE]

00:15:53.850 --> 00:15:59.520
Five 2015 Tony wins, including
best musical score, and best

00:15:59.520 --> 00:16:01.650
book, and of course
best musical.

00:16:01.650 --> 00:16:05.420
And so it was adapted from
Alison Bechdel's graphic novel,

00:16:05.420 --> 00:16:07.210
which, in real
life, the story is

00:16:07.210 --> 00:16:10.340
about the character of Alison,
which the three of them

00:16:10.340 --> 00:16:13.120
play over various times.

00:16:13.120 --> 00:16:15.520
And recreating, basically--
it's essentially

00:16:15.520 --> 00:16:21.184
a graphic novel autobiography,
right, more or less?

00:16:21.184 --> 00:16:21.850
LISA KRON: Yeah.

00:16:21.850 --> 00:16:27.490
I mean, it's a memoir,
so I think it's maybe

00:16:27.490 --> 00:16:28.640
a subtle distinction.

00:16:28.640 --> 00:16:32.120
But I think as opposed to
an autobiography, which

00:16:32.120 --> 00:16:36.510
is about telling the story
of things that happened,

00:16:36.510 --> 00:16:39.150
I think in a memoir
there's something

00:16:39.150 --> 00:16:40.580
essayistic about Alison's work.

00:16:40.580 --> 00:16:43.110
And I think she's
interrogating questions

00:16:43.110 --> 00:16:46.040
about who her father was,
about her relationship

00:16:46.040 --> 00:16:52.100
with her father,
and about memory,

00:16:52.100 --> 00:16:56.300
and the relationship of memory
to what actually happened.

00:16:56.300 --> 00:16:59.150
ALAN SEALES: So how did you even
come across the graphic novel?

00:16:59.150 --> 00:17:00.030
LISA KRON: Doesn't that
sound like a fun musical?

00:17:00.030 --> 00:17:00.905
ALAN SEALES: It does.

00:17:00.905 --> 00:17:01.860
[LAUGHTER]

00:17:01.860 --> 00:17:04.000
And it actually is funny.

00:17:04.000 --> 00:17:04.750
We'll get to that.

00:17:04.750 --> 00:17:06.124
JEANINE TESORI:
It is very funny.

00:17:06.124 --> 00:17:09.069
ALAN SEALES: But how did
you find the graphic novel?

00:17:09.069 --> 00:17:13.920
What light went off saying, oh,
this needs to be on Broadway?

00:17:13.920 --> 00:17:16.700
JEANINE TESORI: Well, the words
triagiocomic graphic novel

00:17:16.700 --> 00:17:17.382
memoir--

00:17:17.382 --> 00:17:18.840
LISA KRON: I mean,
come on, people.

00:17:18.840 --> 00:17:19.280
Come on.

00:17:19.280 --> 00:17:20.571
JEANINE TESORI: Musical comedy.

00:17:20.571 --> 00:17:21.540
Bam, bam, bam.

00:17:21.540 --> 00:17:23.520
Well, you know,
Lisa sent it to me,

00:17:23.520 --> 00:17:26.349
and I don't know if any of
you have read that book.

00:17:26.349 --> 00:17:28.010
I had not, I'm
embarrassed to say.

00:17:28.010 --> 00:17:31.460
And as soon as I read
it, I thought, oh my God,

00:17:31.460 --> 00:17:33.310
that's going to be
a fantastic musical.

00:17:33.310 --> 00:17:35.380
It really sings.

00:17:35.380 --> 00:17:37.450
Getting there is
going to be hellish.

00:17:37.450 --> 00:17:41.240
And it was, because the
book is so beautiful,

00:17:41.240 --> 00:17:43.120
and you have to-- at
one point, I think,

00:17:43.120 --> 00:17:44.310
when you're adapting
something, you

00:17:44.310 --> 00:17:45.726
have to what my
friend calls there

00:17:45.726 --> 00:17:47.300
has to be a lot of
spit on the page,

00:17:47.300 --> 00:17:50.340
when you actually spit at
the very thing that you love

00:17:50.340 --> 00:17:51.380
and make it your own.

00:17:51.380 --> 00:17:53.460
You have to render
that person invisible,

00:17:53.460 --> 00:17:56.700
like actors render us invisible
when they-- though we're

00:17:56.700 --> 00:17:58.720
very visible, they
render us invisible

00:17:58.720 --> 00:18:01.880
when they're on stage, as
if it wasn't ever written,

00:18:01.880 --> 00:18:03.250
it just always was.

00:18:03.250 --> 00:18:06.410
And that was the trick with
that book, the pressure.

00:18:06.410 --> 00:18:09.110
ALAN SEALES: I mean, so you
found the book and you read it.

00:18:09.110 --> 00:18:10.651
But what was the
point when you said,

00:18:10.651 --> 00:18:12.792
I want to turn this
into a Broadway show?

00:18:12.792 --> 00:18:14.000
BETH MALONE: A Broadway show.

00:18:14.000 --> 00:18:15.725
ALAN SEALES: A Broadway--

00:18:15.725 --> 00:18:18.350
JEANINE TESORI: I never thought
this show would be on Broadway.

00:18:18.350 --> 00:18:18.970
I mean, let's be real.

00:18:18.970 --> 00:18:19.990
ALAN SEALES: Did you not?

00:18:19.990 --> 00:18:20.490
JOE: No.

00:18:20.490 --> 00:18:22.170
I've been doing
this since I was 19.

00:18:22.170 --> 00:18:24.740
I was at Columbia and
then I played in the pit.

00:18:24.740 --> 00:18:26.700
I've seen what goes to Broadway.

00:18:26.700 --> 00:18:28.770
It was not this show.

00:18:28.770 --> 00:18:30.020
I thought you just fell over.

00:18:30.020 --> 00:18:33.250
I was like, oh my God.

00:18:33.250 --> 00:18:34.880
I meant, it was
always meant for-- no,

00:18:34.880 --> 00:18:37.984
I just think that Broadway has
cracked open in a way that--

00:18:37.984 --> 00:18:39.400
BETH MALONE: Sorry,
I'm upstaging,

00:18:39.400 --> 00:18:41.400
because that's what I do.

00:18:41.400 --> 00:18:42.852
[LAUGHTER]

00:18:42.852 --> 00:18:45.060
JEANINE TESORI: Beth, what
are your thoughts on that?

00:18:45.060 --> 00:18:45.870
BETH MALONE: You
know, basically,

00:18:45.870 --> 00:18:47.930
when I first received the
script from my agent--

00:18:47.930 --> 00:18:48.430
[LAUGHTER]

00:18:48.430 --> 00:18:51.090
I was like, this is going
straight to Broadway

00:18:51.090 --> 00:18:53.766
and it's going to get me my
Tony nomination, finally.

00:18:53.766 --> 00:18:55.140
And that's exactly
what happened.

00:18:55.140 --> 00:18:55.812
[LAUGHTER]

00:18:55.812 --> 00:18:57.770
ALAN SEALES: And that's
all the time we've got.

00:18:57.770 --> 00:18:58.460
Thank you guys.

00:18:58.460 --> 00:18:59.400
JEANINE TESORI: Yes, goodbye.

00:18:59.400 --> 00:18:59.900
Thank you.

00:19:02.620 --> 00:19:03.832
I have nothing more to add.

00:19:03.832 --> 00:19:05.160
[LAUGHTER]

00:19:05.160 --> 00:19:07.076
ALAN SEALES: Well, so
what were the challenges

00:19:07.076 --> 00:19:09.350
on getting it from your
concept onto the stage?

00:19:09.350 --> 00:19:10.725
JEANINE TESORI:
Well, look at us.

00:19:10.725 --> 00:19:11.845
[LAUGHTER]

00:19:12.970 --> 00:19:14.879
The challenges-- you
guys take that one.

00:19:14.879 --> 00:19:16.420
BETH MALONE: What
are the challenges?

00:19:16.420 --> 00:19:18.290
JEANINE TESORI: Yeah.

00:19:18.290 --> 00:19:20.520
BETH MALONE: Well, OK,
so who's read the book?

00:19:20.520 --> 00:19:21.840
Anybody?

00:19:21.840 --> 00:19:23.906
Yeah, it's like--
you've got to read it.

00:19:23.906 --> 00:19:25.530
Yeah, you should read
it, first of all.

00:19:25.530 --> 00:19:29.130
But first of all, it's really
dense and it's really literate,

00:19:29.130 --> 00:19:32.670
and it does a whole bunch
of things because she can.

00:19:32.670 --> 00:19:36.090
Like, each chapter focuses on
a different literary character,

00:19:36.090 --> 00:19:41.840
and she does all kinds of
literary masturbatory things--

00:19:41.840 --> 00:19:44.620
I mean, fun but awesome
things, because she

00:19:44.620 --> 00:19:46.314
can because she's a genius.

00:19:46.314 --> 00:19:48.730
You know, she's like, I'm going
to make this chapter this,

00:19:48.730 --> 00:19:50.080
and I'm going to do
all these things.

00:19:50.080 --> 00:19:52.371
And you're going to need a
thesaurus to read this book.

00:19:52.371 --> 00:19:56.120
Well, that kind of stuff doesn't
translate into scene work.

00:19:56.120 --> 00:19:59.740
A lot of the scenes, all
of the scenes that you see,

00:19:59.740 --> 00:20:01.180
don't exist in the book.

00:20:01.180 --> 00:20:04.520
So they had to be
created completely

00:20:04.520 --> 00:20:08.180
out of the situations and
the need of the people

00:20:08.180 --> 00:20:10.400
in the moment to
try to figure out

00:20:10.400 --> 00:20:14.545
what happens on a day when this
is what the scene is about,

00:20:14.545 --> 00:20:16.670
and no one's talking about
what the scene is about.

00:20:16.670 --> 00:20:17.670
What do they talk about?

00:20:17.670 --> 00:20:21.220
So there are all kinds
of crazy obstacles

00:20:21.220 --> 00:20:24.240
to getting to the
version that we have now.

00:20:24.240 --> 00:20:25.516
It was insane.

00:20:25.516 --> 00:20:26.890
EMILY SKEGGS: Or
a scene would be

00:20:26.890 --> 00:20:30.640
built around one small
panel of the book.

00:20:30.640 --> 00:20:34.350
One little line and one tiny
drawing, an entire scene

00:20:34.350 --> 00:20:35.520
would be built.

00:20:35.520 --> 00:20:39.480
BETH MALONE: My suggestion
is to just read the play

00:20:39.480 --> 00:20:43.560
and just take apart line by line
just the tree-planting scene.

00:20:43.560 --> 00:20:44.630
This is my favorite.

00:20:44.630 --> 00:20:45.980
I mean, I love the
tree-planting scene.

00:20:45.980 --> 00:20:47.420
LISA KRON: I'm not sure that
would be interesting for them.

00:20:47.420 --> 00:20:48.961
BETH MALONE: Well,
for me, if anybody

00:20:48.961 --> 00:20:54.000
is interested in how dialogue
works to inform you on what--

00:20:54.000 --> 00:20:57.440
like, look at the-- you could
go-- all the information you're

00:20:57.440 --> 00:21:01.680
receiving visually, you have to
receive through conversation.

00:21:01.680 --> 00:21:05.420
That seems natural
and intention based.

00:21:05.420 --> 00:21:07.860
It's crazy what we had to do.

00:21:07.860 --> 00:21:10.330
LISA KRON: This is
sort of a nerdy theater

00:21:10.330 --> 00:21:12.460
conversation that's
happening sort of between us.

00:21:12.460 --> 00:21:18.420
And I think the graphic
novel is extremely literary.

00:21:18.420 --> 00:21:21.280
That being said, it is
extremely accessible.

00:21:21.280 --> 00:21:27.050
It is-- what Alison understands
about the dynamic, engaging

00:21:27.050 --> 00:21:29.920
mechanisms of that
form have made

00:21:29.920 --> 00:21:32.420
her a master, an acknowledged
master, in that field.

00:21:32.420 --> 00:21:35.400
So it's a book that when people
read it, it's the kind of book

00:21:35.400 --> 00:21:37.500
that then they give to
everybody they know.

00:21:37.500 --> 00:21:39.374
They'll buy it for
everybody in their family.

00:21:39.374 --> 00:21:43.830
It's an incredibly moving book.

00:21:43.830 --> 00:21:49.190
There is nothing about
it, about the way

00:21:49.190 --> 00:21:52.230
that it functions, in the way
that it draws the reader in,

00:21:52.230 --> 00:21:56.030
that operates in any
way that's related

00:21:56.030 --> 00:21:58.860
to the way a drama operates.

00:21:58.860 --> 00:22:01.670
So we had to take it apart.

00:22:01.670 --> 00:22:04.150
And it's such a beautifully
made masterpiece

00:22:04.150 --> 00:22:06.670
that it was very difficult
to take it apart,

00:22:06.670 --> 00:22:10.850
because I would try to
read it just to figure out,

00:22:10.850 --> 00:22:14.360
what are the events
in theatrical terms?

00:22:14.360 --> 00:22:18.310
And I would find myself
90 pages in again,

00:22:18.310 --> 00:22:19.300
pulled into the story.

00:22:19.300 --> 00:22:27.530
It was really difficult
to stay, to resist

00:22:27.530 --> 00:22:30.010
the beguilement of
that book enough

00:22:30.010 --> 00:22:34.230
to even see what it was made of,
to see its constituent parts so

00:22:34.230 --> 00:22:38.430
that we could then make them
again in this different way.

00:22:38.430 --> 00:22:41.050
It was incredibly laborious.

00:22:41.050 --> 00:22:46.250
Usually if you can figure out
what the mechanism of a piece

00:22:46.250 --> 00:22:48.670
is-- it's very difficult
to figure it out.

00:22:48.670 --> 00:22:52.450
I always think it's kind
of like throwing a pot.

00:22:52.450 --> 00:22:55.680
You have to-- as I understand
it, not that I'm a potter,

00:22:55.680 --> 00:22:59.670
but you have to center the
clay exactly on the wheel.

00:22:59.670 --> 00:23:02.170
And if you do, then you can
pull it up and make any shape.

00:23:02.170 --> 00:23:05.250
But if you're not exactly
on center, as you pull it up

00:23:05.250 --> 00:23:07.260
it's just going to go
wonky and fall apart.

00:23:07.260 --> 00:23:10.846
And that's what making
plays is like a little bit.

00:23:10.846 --> 00:23:12.262
But plays are much
more forgiving.

00:23:12.262 --> 00:23:13.246
But a musical--

00:23:13.246 --> 00:23:13.740
ALAN SEALES: But this
is your first musical.

00:23:13.740 --> 00:23:14.005
LISA KRON: Yes.

00:23:14.005 --> 00:23:14.590
ALAN SEALES: Yeah.

00:23:14.590 --> 00:23:15.423
JEANINE TESORI: Yes.

00:23:15.423 --> 00:23:17.330
And Lisa won the Tony
on her first one up.

00:23:17.330 --> 00:23:21.085
I must say, I had to
write six musicals

00:23:21.085 --> 00:23:22.960
to get that [MUTED] award.

00:23:22.960 --> 00:23:23.590
But yeah.

00:23:23.590 --> 00:23:25.597
LISA KRON: Obvious we're
meant to work together.

00:23:25.597 --> 00:23:26.805
JEANINE TESORI: It's so true.

00:23:26.805 --> 00:23:29.070
We actually met
writing this musical.

00:23:29.070 --> 00:23:30.070
LISA KRON: Yeah.

00:23:30.070 --> 00:23:31.000
JEANINE TESORI: And
now we're together.

00:23:31.000 --> 00:23:31.974
No, I'm just kidding.

00:23:31.974 --> 00:23:32.948
[LAUGHTER]

00:23:32.948 --> 00:23:33.922
LISA KRON: Exactly.

00:23:33.922 --> 00:23:34.430
JEANINE TESORI: I don't know.

00:23:34.430 --> 00:23:35.120
It's that clock.

00:23:35.120 --> 00:23:37.756
It makes me feel pressured to
say things that aren't true.

00:23:37.756 --> 00:23:39.130
ALAN SEALES: That's
more for me--

00:23:39.130 --> 00:23:40.180
BETH MALONE: What
does that clock mean?

00:23:40.680 --> 00:23:43.210
ALAN SEALES: That's my cue
to know when to wrap it up.

00:23:43.210 --> 00:23:44.540
BETH MALONE: Oh, OK.

00:23:44.540 --> 00:23:45.310
ALAN SEALES: So I
know people have

00:23:45.310 --> 00:23:46.500
to get on with their day jobs.

00:23:46.500 --> 00:23:47.280
We could sit here forever.

00:23:47.280 --> 00:23:48.610
We'll just have a
private conversation.

00:23:48.610 --> 00:23:49.776
They can all do their thing.

00:23:49.776 --> 00:23:52.090
LISA KRON: I keep waiting
for the temperature.

00:23:54.370 --> 00:23:56.370
ALAN SEALES: OK, Google,
what's the temperature.

00:23:56.370 --> 00:23:56.755
JEANINE TESORI: Super cool.

00:23:56.755 --> 00:23:57.140
Super cool.

00:23:57.140 --> 00:23:58.681
ALAN SEALES: Jeanine,
you're actually

00:23:58.681 --> 00:24:01.700
the most prolific and honored
female theatrical composer

00:24:01.700 --> 00:24:03.614
in history.

00:24:03.614 --> 00:24:05.880
BETH MALONE: But can we
just remove the word female

00:24:05.880 --> 00:24:08.230
from that and just talk
about how many musicals

00:24:08.230 --> 00:24:11.200
she's written, and one of
the most prolific composers

00:24:11.200 --> 00:24:12.940
in Broadway history, OK?

00:24:12.940 --> 00:24:13.630
[APPLAUSE]

00:24:13.630 --> 00:24:15.378
First of all.

00:24:15.378 --> 00:24:17.610
Thanks.

