ALAN SEALES: And mic drop.

00:24:19.410 --> 00:24:21.730
So what was it
personally for you

00:24:21.730 --> 00:24:23.750
that made you want
to work on this show?

00:24:23.750 --> 00:24:26.450
You've done so much,
your career is so vast,

00:24:26.450 --> 00:24:28.930
that what was it about this?

00:24:28.930 --> 00:24:32.820
JEANINE TESORI: I grew up
in the '70s, and I'm very,

00:24:32.820 --> 00:24:36.290
you know, tall, grande, venti.

00:24:36.290 --> 00:24:40.660
And that to me is me.

00:24:40.660 --> 00:24:45.270
Not as nice shoes, but we
grew up at the same time,

00:24:45.270 --> 00:24:46.480
the same time as Alison.

00:24:46.480 --> 00:24:49.824
And I remember in the '70s and
thinking through Tiger Beat

00:24:49.824 --> 00:24:52.115
and all of that stuff that
no one here will know about,

00:24:52.115 --> 00:24:53.970
which is so frustrating.

00:24:53.970 --> 00:24:58.270
But I remember being Gabby's
age looking at my parents, who

00:24:58.270 --> 00:25:00.650
were interesting people.

00:25:00.650 --> 00:25:02.480
And there's a whole
inner life, I think,

00:25:02.480 --> 00:25:04.567
that gets stored
versus the outer life.

00:25:04.567 --> 00:25:06.650
And that's where a lot of
musicals, I think, live.

00:25:06.650 --> 00:25:09.220
When you look at a lot
of things when people-- I

00:25:09.220 --> 00:25:11.942
hate the adage, when you
can't speak anymore, you sing.

00:25:11.942 --> 00:25:13.650
I was like, I don't
know what that means.

00:25:13.650 --> 00:25:16.474
What I do know is that we
all have these inner lives,

00:25:16.474 --> 00:25:18.890
and when you think about your
relationship to your parents

00:25:18.890 --> 00:25:23.450
right now and what it was, and
then what it was and what it is

00:25:23.450 --> 00:25:26.340
and what it will be,
there are all these songs.

00:25:26.340 --> 00:25:28.540
And a lot of that
genetic material

00:25:28.540 --> 00:25:30.430
is musical genetic material.

00:25:30.430 --> 00:25:33.250
We are themes and
variations of each other.

00:25:33.250 --> 00:25:34.920
There's no way not to be.

00:25:34.920 --> 00:25:37.960
And so what we tried
to do-- and musically,

00:25:37.960 --> 00:25:40.860
when you look at classical
music does it all the time,

00:25:40.860 --> 00:25:43.410
you take something,
a statement, and then

00:25:43.410 --> 00:25:45.330
you rework it and you rework it.

00:25:45.330 --> 00:25:48.470
And that metaphor of throwing
the pot is exactly right.

00:25:48.470 --> 00:25:50.356
And you think of
all of the shapes--

00:25:50.356 --> 00:25:53.700
Bach did it, Mozart did it
beautifully, all of them.

00:25:53.700 --> 00:25:56.530
And then at the very end,
why they call it the tonic,

00:25:56.530 --> 00:25:57.560
is you come home.

00:25:57.560 --> 00:25:58.860
You come home again.

00:25:58.860 --> 00:26:01.100
And that's what musical
long form is based on.

00:26:01.100 --> 00:26:04.390
So this show absolutely
fell into the path

00:26:04.390 --> 00:26:07.830
of coming home to yourself
and being changed by it,

00:26:07.830 --> 00:26:10.700
the way that "The Odyssey"
works and so much of literature.

00:26:10.700 --> 00:26:14.270
And it's such a smart
structure, this one.

00:26:14.270 --> 00:26:17.250
So I was desperate to do it.

00:26:17.250 --> 00:26:18.920
And I felt the
pressure for it to be

00:26:18.920 --> 00:26:21.290
really as great as the book.

00:26:21.290 --> 00:26:24.410
LISA KRON: As literary
as the book is,

00:26:24.410 --> 00:26:30.190
I think what both of us sensed--
I mean, what I have learned,

00:26:30.190 --> 00:26:32.302
and Jeanine already
knew this, and we

00:26:32.302 --> 00:26:34.510
had a little conversation
with George Wolfe early on,

00:26:34.510 --> 00:26:36.920
and he articulated
this in a way that

00:26:36.920 --> 00:26:39.840
was extremely helpful
to me and I think to us.

00:26:39.840 --> 00:26:42.892
He said, you know, a
musical can be as complex

00:26:42.892 --> 00:26:44.350
as you want it to
be, but there has

00:26:44.350 --> 00:26:50.320
to be one primal desire
that starts the engine

00:26:50.320 --> 00:26:54.800
and drives through every
single moment of the musical.

00:26:54.800 --> 00:26:58.540
And I think what we
sensed was in the book

00:26:58.540 --> 00:27:00.270
and what we put
into the musical is

00:27:00.270 --> 00:27:01.630
that there's a primal desire.

00:27:01.630 --> 00:27:04.200
It's the first lines
of the musical,

00:27:04.200 --> 00:27:07.680
Gabby comes out and sings, and
she sings it in the finale,

00:27:07.680 --> 00:27:10.490
as you heard, and Beth is
writing it, Daddy, hey Daddy,

00:27:10.490 --> 00:27:14.580
come here, I need you-- the
primal desire of a child

00:27:14.580 --> 00:27:17.570
to make a physical
connection with her father,

00:27:17.570 --> 00:27:20.250
in this case a father
who is very withholding,

00:27:20.250 --> 00:27:24.420
and that desire, which
everyone has a relationship to,

00:27:24.420 --> 00:27:26.020
no matter who your parent is.

00:27:26.020 --> 00:27:29.270
If you didn't know your
parent, you know that desire.

00:27:29.270 --> 00:27:30.920
It's a primal need.

00:27:30.920 --> 00:27:32.570
And it's in the book.

00:27:32.570 --> 00:27:36.250
It's what makes people feel
the way they do about the book.

00:27:36.250 --> 00:27:39.901
And it's a perfect
core for a musical.

