00:32:02.720 --> 00:32:04.420
So the format of
the show itself is

00:32:04.420 --> 00:32:06.780
in the round, which, for
those who don't know,

00:32:06.780 --> 00:32:09.870
the audience is sitting 360
degrees around the stage.

00:32:09.870 --> 00:32:13.080
And that's very, very
unusual for Broadway.

00:32:13.080 --> 00:32:15.480
And this is now
the third staging

00:32:15.480 --> 00:32:19.120
of the show, the previous
two not in the round.

00:32:19.120 --> 00:32:21.810
How did it get to where it
is, and why does it work?

00:32:21.810 --> 00:32:24.320
Why did you choose this version?

00:32:24.320 --> 00:32:26.180
Anybody?

00:32:26.180 --> 00:32:27.410
JEANINE TESORI: Yeah, Sam--

00:32:27.410 --> 00:32:28.660
ALAN SEALES: Sam the director.

00:32:28.660 --> 00:32:30.640
JEANINE TESORI: We did
it-- a thrust stage,

00:32:30.640 --> 00:32:33.930
and then proscenium
at The Public.

00:32:33.930 --> 00:32:36.370
Part of it is Sam loves
working in the round.

00:32:36.370 --> 00:32:38.930
Musicals are almost never in
the round because of the way

00:32:38.930 --> 00:32:40.070
that sound design is.

00:32:40.070 --> 00:32:43.900
You know, just think that you
have to look at someone often

00:32:43.900 --> 00:32:46.030
to be able to--
like at a concert,

00:32:46.030 --> 00:32:49.650
to watch someone play you
listen to it very differently.

00:32:49.650 --> 00:32:53.270
And when the image is
removed from the sound,

00:32:53.270 --> 00:32:54.350
it's much harder.

00:32:54.350 --> 00:32:57.440
But the sound design by Kai
Harada and the technology--

00:32:57.440 --> 00:32:59.570
we're at Google,
so you know, is so

00:32:59.570 --> 00:33:02.390
amazing you can throw this
imagery onto the stage.

00:33:02.390 --> 00:33:05.110
And even if that person isn't
there, it's like they're there.

00:33:05.110 --> 00:33:07.510
And that's a whole
new age for us

00:33:07.510 --> 00:33:10.360
at musicals, because
you can do it very,

00:33:10.360 --> 00:33:12.690
very differently than the
traditional proscenium

00:33:12.690 --> 00:33:15.330
arch, which requires
that there is focus.

00:33:15.330 --> 00:33:17.070
And you can do it
really differently.

00:33:17.070 --> 00:33:20.380
It's also a memory play,
so this fits beautifully

00:33:20.380 --> 00:33:23.360
inside that idea that memory can
come and get you at any point.

00:33:23.360 --> 00:33:26.040
It's getting me right now.

00:33:26.040 --> 00:33:29.660
So the people who are in
power are not the actors.

00:33:29.660 --> 00:33:31.490
It's the audience
who's in power.

00:33:31.490 --> 00:33:33.031
ALAN SEALES: It was
interesting to me

00:33:33.031 --> 00:33:34.670
because halfway
through, I realized

00:33:34.670 --> 00:33:37.490
that I felt like I was
literally inside the mind

00:33:37.490 --> 00:33:38.620
of the storyteller.

00:33:38.620 --> 00:33:42.020
It is Broadway-sized, obviously,
it's an on-Broadway show,

00:33:42.020 --> 00:33:44.850
but it feels very intimate.

00:33:44.850 --> 00:33:49.640
And the stage itself, there's
the living room of the house,

00:33:49.640 --> 00:33:52.060
and then there are times
when the whole furniture just

00:33:52.060 --> 00:33:54.680
shifts, so we see
different sides of it.

00:33:54.680 --> 00:34:00.900
And I feel like it just worked
so incredibly well to convey--

00:34:00.900 --> 00:34:03.400
I was reading, I won't take
credit for this terminology,

00:34:03.400 --> 00:34:06.300
but the swirling of
the memories going on

00:34:06.300 --> 00:34:08.300
and the recollection of
the character of Alison,

00:34:08.300 --> 00:34:11.000
because the whole
thing is a flashback.

00:34:11.000 --> 00:34:12.630
So there's no question there.

00:34:12.630 --> 00:34:15.004
BETH MALONE: But it doesn't
necessarily behave in the way

00:34:15.004 --> 00:34:18.530
