00:35:05.010 --> 00:35:06.532
JEANINE TESORI: "Fantastic
Journey" with Raquel Welch,

00:35:06.532 --> 00:35:07.427
where they go in--

00:35:07.427 --> 00:35:08.760
ALAN SEALES: "Fantastic Voyage"?

00:35:08.760 --> 00:35:09.850
JEANINE TESORI: Thank you.

00:35:09.850 --> 00:35:10.930
Oh my God, you have to see it.

00:35:10.930 --> 00:35:12.971
And then they get attacked
by a white blood cell.

00:35:12.971 --> 00:35:13.980
BETH MALONE: Yes.

00:35:13.980 --> 00:35:15.521
JEANINE TESORI: She
wears a jumpsuit.

00:35:15.521 --> 00:35:17.246
It's so amazing.

00:35:17.246 --> 00:35:19.170
ALAN SEALES: You had
a question over here?

00:35:19.170 --> 00:35:21.656
AUDIENCE: Yeah, I was
wondering, Alison Bechdel,

00:35:21.656 --> 00:35:23.805
did she participate in
the writing process,

00:35:23.805 --> 00:35:25.940
or did she just
hand you her baby?

00:35:25.940 --> 00:35:28.290
And did she like the end result?

00:35:28.290 --> 00:35:30.170
LISA KRON: She
handed us her baby,

00:35:30.170 --> 00:35:32.140
and she made herself available.

00:35:32.140 --> 00:35:35.479
She gave us her journals that
she wrote-- me and Jeanine,

00:35:35.479 --> 00:35:37.520
she gave us her journals
that she wrote while she

00:35:37.520 --> 00:35:38.990
was writing "Fun Home."

00:35:38.990 --> 00:35:45.640
And she was available to
answer our questions which

00:35:45.640 --> 00:35:46.830
came up in the writing.

00:35:46.830 --> 00:35:49.320
But then she really trusted us.

00:35:49.320 --> 00:35:52.700
And it was, indeed, like
handing us her baby.

00:35:52.700 --> 00:35:57.760
And she, yes, I
think unequivocally

00:35:57.760 --> 00:36:00.510
feels very positive
about the show

00:36:00.510 --> 00:36:02.340
and I think very
connected to the show.

00:36:02.340 --> 00:36:04.510
And on the night I think,
we opened at The Public,

00:36:04.510 --> 00:36:06.270
or maybe it was
around that time,

00:36:06.270 --> 00:36:10.370
and she said, I don't
know what to do.

00:36:10.370 --> 00:36:11.984
She expresses her
gratitude a lot.

00:36:11.984 --> 00:36:14.400
And she said, I feel like I
should give you my first born.

00:36:14.400 --> 00:36:15.530
And then there was
this sort of pause

00:36:15.530 --> 00:36:17.116
and we looked at each other,
and we were like, well,

00:36:17.116 --> 00:36:17.910
you did already.

00:36:17.910 --> 00:36:19.035
ALAN SEALES: You did, yeah.

00:36:19.035 --> 00:36:19.814
[LAUGHTER]

00:36:19.814 --> 00:36:21.501
Yeah, question?

00:36:21.501 --> 00:36:23.250
AUDIENCE: First of
all, thank you so much.

00:36:23.250 --> 00:36:24.420
The performance was amazing.

00:36:24.420 --> 00:36:26.530
Really appreciate it.

00:36:26.530 --> 00:36:30.360
So this is a question primarily
for the three Alisons.

00:36:30.360 --> 00:36:32.969
This is obviously a very
deeply personal story.

00:36:32.969 --> 00:36:35.260
I mean, I haven't read the
book or seen the whole show,

00:36:35.260 --> 00:36:38.347
and just those three songs were
giving me the feels back here.

00:36:38.347 --> 00:36:39.472
ALAN SEALES: All the feels.

00:36:39.472 --> 00:36:40.472
AUDIENCE: All the feels.

00:36:40.472 --> 00:36:42.250
All at the same time.

00:36:42.250 --> 00:36:45.550
But my question is, for
you guys as somebody who's

00:36:45.550 --> 00:36:48.200
interpreting this deeply
personal experience

00:36:48.200 --> 00:36:49.960
and then projecting
it for other people,

00:36:49.960 --> 00:36:51.730
how do you tap into that?

00:36:51.730 --> 00:36:54.230
How do you personally
approach making

00:36:54.230 --> 00:36:57.100
that accessible to
people like me, this lump

00:36:57.100 --> 00:36:59.630
sitting in the back of the room?

00:36:59.630 --> 00:37:01.110
EMILY SKEGGS: Yeah,
I think there's

00:37:01.110 --> 00:37:03.170
a lot about the story
that's really specific.

00:37:03.170 --> 00:37:08.459
But the end of the day,
it's a story about a girl

00:37:08.459 --> 00:37:10.000
and her relationship
with her father,

00:37:10.000 --> 00:37:12.230
and her relationship
with her sexuality.

00:37:12.230 --> 00:37:15.410
And I think it's pretty safe
to say that we all have fathers

00:37:15.410 --> 00:37:17.310
in some way, shape, or form.

00:37:17.310 --> 00:37:20.900
And we all have some kind
of desire for other people.

00:37:20.900 --> 00:37:26.500
And so I think that just
keeping that in mind.

00:37:26.500 --> 00:37:29.310
And it's about empathy.

00:37:29.310 --> 00:37:31.760
It's about finding a
connection with these people,

00:37:31.760 --> 00:37:36.360
these real, live
people, that-- you know,

00:37:36.360 --> 00:37:39.140
Alison has a struggle
with her father,

00:37:39.140 --> 00:37:41.320
but they both have
the same struggle.

00:37:41.320 --> 00:37:42.706
Another stoner thought for you.

00:37:42.706 --> 00:37:43.380
BETH MALONE: I love it.

00:37:43.380 --> 00:37:44.010
EMILY SKEGGS: Do you
know what I mean?

00:37:44.010 --> 00:37:45.030
BETH MALONE: Yes.

00:37:45.030 --> 00:37:45.650
For me--

00:37:45.650 --> 00:37:46.800
EMILY SKEGGS: It's
about connection.

00:37:46.800 --> 00:37:47.080
BETH MALONE: Yes.

00:37:47.080 --> 00:37:47.910
EMILY SKEGGS: They
have the same struggle,

00:37:47.910 --> 00:37:49.070
but they don't know
how to talk about it.

00:37:49.070 --> 00:37:50.653
BETH MALONE: There's
a lot about being

00:37:50.653 --> 00:37:53.950
in the show that lends itself
to the actual material that is

00:37:53.950 --> 00:37:55.540
like, I don't want to do that.

00:37:55.540 --> 00:37:56.530
I don't want to go.

00:37:56.530 --> 00:37:58.020
I don't want to
watch this scene.

00:37:58.020 --> 00:37:59.430
I don't want to watch it.

00:37:59.430 --> 00:38:02.680
I don't want to have to watch
him leave these kids in a New

00:38:02.680 --> 00:38:04.100
York apartment
while he goes off.

00:38:04.100 --> 00:38:05.350
I don't want to watch this.

00:38:05.350 --> 00:38:07.790
And that actually is helpful.

00:38:07.790 --> 00:38:11.170
There's a lot about
being in the show,

00:38:11.170 --> 00:38:15.780
and you have to give-- you
must give yourself over to it.

00:38:15.780 --> 00:38:17.560
To be in the show,
there are things

00:38:17.560 --> 00:38:19.620
that you're going to
not want to have to do.

00:38:19.620 --> 00:38:21.890
But that's exactly the journey.

00:38:21.890 --> 00:38:24.940
That's the exact
journey of Alison going,

00:38:24.940 --> 00:38:27.250
whoa, I wanted to make
this piece of art,

00:38:27.250 --> 00:38:29.682
but I didn't know it
was going to do this.

00:38:29.682 --> 00:38:31.890
I didn't know it was going
to take me here and there.

00:38:31.890 --> 00:38:34.919
And that's the same as kind
of being in it sometimes.

00:38:34.919 --> 00:38:36.460
It's like, wow, I
really wanted this.

00:38:36.460 --> 00:38:38.260
I really wanted
to make this art.

00:38:38.260 --> 00:38:41.410
Agh, it's awful.

00:38:41.410 --> 00:38:43.000
But it's wonderful.

00:38:43.000 --> 00:38:46.040
So there's a lot of, at that
moment to moment thing, when

00:38:46.040 --> 00:38:48.040
the show starts, da
da, da da, da da,

00:38:48.040 --> 00:38:50.610
and you just kind of
walk through that door

00:38:50.610 --> 00:38:52.870
and it just kind
of sucks you in.

00:38:52.870 --> 00:38:56.580
And the moment to moment
work of the composers

00:38:56.580 --> 00:38:58.390
and the lyricists
and the book writer

00:38:58.390 --> 00:39:01.320
have given us sort of a
template where we just

00:39:01.320 --> 00:39:04.630
have to step out on
stage, and it takes you

00:39:04.630 --> 00:39:05.630
right down the road.

00:39:05.630 --> 00:39:08.390
EMILY SKEGGS: The material
is like a pull of honesty.

00:39:08.390 --> 00:39:09.150
BETH MALONE: Yeah.

00:39:09.150 --> 00:39:12.579
It's like there's no
fat left in this script.

00:39:12.579 --> 00:39:13.787
I did an interview yesterday.

00:39:13.787 --> 00:39:15.328
Somebody was like,
well, this version

00:39:15.328 --> 00:39:19.090
of the character-- I'm like,
there's just no character left.

00:39:19.090 --> 00:39:22.210
It's all just--
it's just intention.

00:39:22.210 --> 00:39:23.170
That's all that's left.

00:39:23.170 --> 00:39:28.500
It's like there's no-- it's just
an elegant, streamlined person

00:39:28.500 --> 00:39:32.310
voraciously searching for
something a minute at a time.

00:39:32.310 --> 00:39:34.220
So that's all it is.

00:39:34.220 --> 00:39:39.240
LISA KRON: I think what
we're trying to do,

00:39:39.240 --> 00:39:41.330
what theater makers
try to do, is

00:39:41.330 --> 00:39:44.300
to make something that
will do what you just

00:39:44.300 --> 00:39:46.070
described, is to
give an audience,

00:39:46.070 --> 00:39:48.190
to evoke feeling
from an audience.

00:39:48.190 --> 00:39:51.700
And it costs us something
sometimes to do it.

00:39:51.700 --> 00:39:55.030
But the thing is
made out of craft.

00:39:55.030 --> 00:40:00.970
And so what you feel
and what we have made

00:40:00.970 --> 00:40:04.580
are actually not the same thing.

00:40:04.580 --> 00:40:09.410
We make this sort
of vessel of craft

00:40:09.410 --> 00:40:12.930
that then takes you someplace.

00:40:15.864 --> 00:40:18.030
And it should feel-- you
shouldn't think about that.

00:40:18.030 --> 00:40:18.790
You should never
think about that.

00:40:18.790 --> 00:40:20.570
We also want to
make you-- we want

00:40:20.570 --> 00:40:23.310
to make something that is lean
in the way Beth's talking about

00:40:23.310 --> 00:40:25.880
so that you never--
the goal is for you

00:40:25.880 --> 00:40:27.620
to get picked up and
carried somewhere,

00:40:27.620 --> 00:40:33.920
and never be thinking
about that craft.

00:40:33.920 --> 00:40:37.270
But I think what it seems
like is that what you feel

00:40:37.270 --> 00:40:39.860
is identical to
what we are doing.

00:40:39.860 --> 00:40:40.660
And it's actually--

00:40:40.660 --> 00:40:44.530
BETH MALONE: All I have to say,
what you bring to this room

00:40:44.530 --> 00:40:47.272
is what "Fun Home" does to you.

00:40:47.272 --> 00:40:51.100
You sit in that seat and you
brought whatever relationships

00:40:51.100 --> 00:40:54.200
you have in your life
to this viewing today.

00:40:54.200 --> 00:40:56.290
And that's the thing
you're feeling.

00:40:56.290 --> 00:40:57.550
That's what you're feeling.

00:40:57.550 --> 00:40:58.360
We do this thing.

00:40:58.360 --> 00:40:59.830
We do the same thing
every day, and everybody

00:40:59.830 --> 00:41:01.829
was like, oh my God, the
show was about suicide.

00:41:01.829 --> 00:41:03.740
Oh my God, the show is
about mental illness.

00:41:03.740 --> 00:41:05.630
The show was about being
gay and coming out.

00:41:05.630 --> 00:41:08.780
It was like, it's about
whatever it's about.

00:41:08.780 --> 00:41:10.920
You bring so much of it,
because there's so much

00:41:10.920 --> 00:41:12.300
empty space in the show.

00:41:12.300 --> 00:41:15.980
There's a lot of
room for you to fill

00:41:15.980 --> 00:41:18.671
in your own narrative in your
own experience in "Fun Home,"

00:41:18.671 --> 00:41:19.170
I think.

00:41:19.170 --> 00:41:22.490
It's not super busy
and rattling your mind

00:41:22.490 --> 00:41:27.300
with every measure
filled with-- cram-packed

00:41:27.300 --> 00:41:28.950
with words and beats.

00:41:28.950 --> 00:41:33.567
It's like there's emptiness
for you to show up.

00:41:33.567 --> 00:41:35.650
ALAN SEALES: We're actually
running short on time,

00:41:35.650 --> 00:41:36.890
so we'll do one
more question here.

00:41:36.890 --> 00:41:37.160
Yeah.

00:41:37.160 --> 00:41:37.701
JOE: Awesome.

00:41:37.701 --> 00:41:38.910
Hi, I'm Joe.

00:41:38.910 --> 00:41:40.630
I went to school for
music, and something

00:41:40.630 --> 00:41:42.046
about the music
that really struck

00:41:42.046 --> 00:41:44.760
me was that it seemed to
combine so many different

00:41:44.760 --> 00:41:47.510
influences-- classical,
modern music.

00:41:47.510 --> 00:41:50.070
And it wasn't one of
those musicals that

00:41:50.070 --> 00:41:54.980
takes a great artist and makes a
musical out of their past work.

00:41:54.980 --> 00:41:56.270
It really invents new music.

00:41:56.270 --> 00:41:59.420
And I was wondering if you
could talk about your sources

00:41:59.420 --> 00:42:02.950
for that, and if you could
talk about how you approached

00:42:02.950 --> 00:42:04.970
writing for three
different people, three

00:42:04.970 --> 00:42:09.670
different parts of their
life, and if the music matured

00:42:09.670 --> 00:42:11.429
in any ways that you found.

00:42:11.429 --> 00:42:13.012
JEANINE TESORI: Such
a great question.

00:42:13.012 --> 00:42:17.390
You should probably
be composing.

00:42:17.390 --> 00:42:20.280
Well, I have so much recall.

00:42:20.280 --> 00:42:24.280
I remember reading Judy
Blume when I was at that age,

00:42:24.280 --> 00:42:26.780
"Are You there God, It's Me,
Margaret," and thinking, God,

00:42:26.780 --> 00:42:29.360
is this written
by an 11-year-old?

00:42:29.360 --> 00:42:32.070
And she said that
she has this recall.

00:42:32.070 --> 00:42:33.850
And I have that.

00:42:33.850 --> 00:42:38.480
I have a kind of mind
that is complicated.

00:42:38.480 --> 00:42:40.410
There's a bar mitzvah
always going on.

00:42:40.410 --> 00:42:45.200
But every-- I remember-- I'm
not Jewish, and I'm straight

00:42:45.200 --> 00:42:49.860
and it's just a
problem on both sides.

00:42:49.860 --> 00:42:53.910
So I have so much-- my training
was so odd and wonderful that I

00:42:53.910 --> 00:42:57.629
was trained classically, and
my piano teacher absolutely

00:42:57.629 --> 00:42:59.420
demanded-- you know,
it's interesting we're

00:42:59.420 --> 00:43:03.210
talking about space,
and I had space

00:43:03.210 --> 00:43:06.710
to improvise and to do lead
sheets and circle of fifths

00:43:06.710 --> 00:43:10.090
in everything, and to play
TV themes and pop music.

00:43:10.090 --> 00:43:12.980
And I grew up speaking
four or five languages.

00:43:12.980 --> 00:43:16.340
And sometimes people
have-- about my work,

00:43:16.340 --> 00:43:19.050
they say it's pastichey or
it's eclectic, which means,

00:43:19.050 --> 00:43:19.740
you suck.

00:43:19.740 --> 00:43:21.520
In my world, that's
what it means.

00:43:21.520 --> 00:43:22.320
Trust me.

00:43:22.320 --> 00:43:25.680
But for me, it's that
idea that I am-- I

00:43:25.680 --> 00:43:28.140
love what Beth was just
saying, that you are what

00:43:28.140 --> 00:43:30.100
you bring to all these things.

00:43:30.100 --> 00:43:34.810
And I find in "Fun Home," I
finally-- I didn't find it,

00:43:34.810 --> 00:43:36.120
Lisa found it.

00:43:36.120 --> 00:43:38.420
And because I am
all of these three,

00:43:38.420 --> 00:43:40.690
I should be so lucky to
be these three people.

00:43:40.690 --> 00:43:42.400
But we are these nesting dolls.

00:43:42.400 --> 00:43:44.910
And I feel like a
nesting doll musically.

00:43:44.910 --> 00:43:48.220
I love the Talking Heads,
and I love Stravinsky.

00:43:48.220 --> 00:43:51.980
And I loved R. Kelly
"In the Closet."

00:43:51.980 --> 00:43:54.610
I mean, all of that, all of
those things, and the beat.

00:43:54.610 --> 00:43:57.380
And I was trained in
Nashville, and I finally

00:43:57.380 --> 00:44:01.260
found this place where I could
access so much of those things,

00:44:01.260 --> 00:44:05.840
trying to not apologize
for being so many things,

00:44:05.840 --> 00:44:08.230
because I think a lot of women,
I don't know about people

00:44:08.230 --> 00:44:11.010
in this room, were
taught, and I think told,

00:44:11.010 --> 00:44:13.230
as I was, you are too much.

00:44:13.230 --> 00:44:16.410
And I said that to someone
recently, and they said,

00:44:16.410 --> 00:44:19.150
you mean too much for
them, for those people

00:44:19.150 --> 00:44:20.240
who are telling you that.

00:44:20.240 --> 00:44:22.794
And I thought, oh, if I had
known that 20 years ago.

00:44:22.794 --> 00:44:24.186
[LAUGHTER]

00:44:26.040 --> 00:44:29.170
ALAN SEALES: So Gabby,
has your relationship

00:44:29.170 --> 00:44:32.890
with your parents changed
since you've been in the show?

00:44:32.890 --> 00:44:35.352
[LAUGHTER]

00:44:35.352 --> 00:44:36.852
JEANINE TESORI:
Your mother is here.

00:44:36.852 --> 00:44:38.970
GABRIELLA PIZZOLO: Yes.

00:44:38.970 --> 00:44:39.980
No.

00:44:39.980 --> 00:44:45.500
My parents have always both
been very, very supportive of me

00:44:45.500 --> 00:44:49.020
and very, very helpful,
and that has never

00:44:49.020 --> 00:44:50.680
changed all of my life.

00:44:50.680 --> 00:44:52.596
JEANINE TESORI: God,
what does that feel like?

00:44:52.596 --> 00:44:53.496
[APPLAUSE]

00:44:55.186 --> 00:44:56.310
ALAN SEALES: Good job, Mom.

00:44:56.310 --> 00:44:58.120
Good job.

00:44:58.120 --> 00:45:01.540
So just last question here,
could be an upper or downer,

00:45:01.540 --> 00:45:03.780
I guess.

00:45:03.780 --> 00:45:05.910
You bring to it what you will.

00:45:05.910 --> 00:45:08.040
What advice would
any of you give

00:45:08.040 --> 00:45:12.620
to a child who suspects
that their parents, one

00:45:12.620 --> 00:45:14.880
of their parents might
be gay, or a parent who

00:45:14.880 --> 00:45:19.266
suspects one of their
children might be gay?

00:45:19.266 --> 00:45:21.060
JEANINE TESORI: Gabby,
why don't you start?

00:45:21.060 --> 00:45:21.976
GABRIELLA PIZZOLO: OK.

00:45:21.976 --> 00:45:22.476
[LAUGHTER]

00:45:22.476 --> 00:45:31.850
I would say just understanding
that people have a right

00:45:31.850 --> 00:45:35.020
to be who they want to be.

00:45:35.020 --> 00:45:37.304
ALAN SEALES: All right.

00:45:37.304 --> 00:45:38.680
[APPLAUSE]

00:45:38.680 --> 00:45:41.560
GABRIELLA PIZZOLO:
Whoever they are.

00:45:41.560 --> 00:45:43.236
ALAN SEALES: Well,
I guess that's it.

00:45:43.236 --> 00:45:45.860
All right, well, everybody give
them another round of applause.

00:45:45.860 --> 00:45:47.583
Thank you so much for coming in.

00:45:47.583 --> 00:45:49.998
[APPLAUSE]

00:45:52.880 --> 00:45:53.380
Cool.

00:45:53.380 --> 00:45:55.490
Thank you so much.

